There were two bouts of Male Chorus detected, with the first bout being followed by Female Chatter, indicating a bout of Incubation. Approximately 26 days after the cessation of Male Chorus, the first Fledgling Begging Calls are heard, which correlates perfectly with the expected date if Incubation started just after the cessation of the first bout of Male Chorus (31-May). Onset of the second bout of Male Chorus coincides with the expected onset of Brooding (12-Jun). I have noted that many colonies have a burst of Male Chorus right at onset of Brooding.
column84: Both T27.1 and T27.2 were converted from fallow rice to wetland in 2013 and managed as seasonal wetland until 2014. Pond management includes winter overwater prescribed fire, sheep grazing (they will be detected on the audio recording), and mowing/disking.  Additional details are available upon request.

column78: This site was initially analyzed before pattern matching algorithms were available, and recordings were manually analyzed. Later Pattern Matching analysis was developed and the site was reanalyzed using these new tools. When compared, the two analyses did not agree for the first nesting attempt, and revisiting the manual analysis revealed that there were some errors in my assignment to Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls. These Begging Calls in early May are from another species. There are a handful of Tricolored Blackbird Hatchling and Fledgling calls May 1-3, but then they stop. So, this first nesting attempt was abandoned. Subsequently, there was a Retry Nesting attempt that started shortly after the Abandonment as well as a third nesting attempt in June. The second and third nesting attempts successfully produced fledglings. Unfortunately for the second nesting attempt in May, there are a few days that coincide with onset of Brooding where the recordings are unusable. Thus, the dates for onset of Brooding in late May are potentially a day or two earlier than reported. NOTE - I have detailed notes from regular site visits.

column78: The ARU used was an LG phone running Arbimon software. Recordings made using these devices resulted in faint sonograms, and pattern matching algorithms did not work well. Note this site had manual analysis as it was initially analyzed before pattern matching was available, dates in May where no vocalizations were detected were due to lack of recordings that were caused by the LG recorder crashing and needing to be rebooted. column78: Although a small number of Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations were detected early in the deployment, they declined rapidly, and neither Female Chatter nor Begging Calls occurred at sufficient levels to indicate colony establishment. Vocal activity was largely absent after the first several days, consistent with birds abandoning the area. Construction adjacent to the site may have contributed to the lack of establishment.
column84: Tricolored Blackbirds nested in a 0.2-ha patch of Himalayan Blackberry in a small area designated as open space surrounded by roadways, commercial stores, parking lots, and a housing development. Commercial and residential construction occurred within 80 m of the nesting site in 2018, and construction activities continued during the breeding period.

column78: The ARU used was an LG phone running Arbimon software. Recordings made using these devices resulted in faint sonograms, and pattern matching algorithms did not work well. Manual analysis of the recordings allowed for detection of vocalizations. The ARU was placed after Incubation started, and only a handful of recordings contained Hatchling Begging Calls. The day with multiple recordings with Hatchling Begging Calls was 17-May, and 5 days later no Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations were heard.  Note this site had intense manual analysis as it was initially analyzed before pattern matching was available.

Fledgling Begging Calls were detected early in the deployment that likely originated from an adjacent portion of the colony where fledging had already begun. Later-stage Begging Calls reflected the attempt recorded by this ARU. Despite reduced signal quality and incomplete data due to device failure late in the deployment, the presence of Fledgling Begging Calls confirms successful reproduction. The colony was adjacent to an active wetland mitigation construction project, though construction was halted around the colony during the breeding period and did not appear to affect breeding success.

column84: The Denverton Creek colony site is in a cattle ranch field in Solano County, California, (38.241, −121.888) at 9.0 m elevation. column78: Unlike the nearby Denverton Creek colony, the second nesting attempt was not initiated until after the rain in mid-May, and both attempts were successful, though the second attempt was Partially Abandoned. There was a 4 day period of 90+F right at onset of Brooding.  NOTE - I have detailed notes from regular site visits. Second attempt was partially abandoned.
column84: The Hay Landfill colony site is in a mitigation pond adjacent to the Hay Road Landfill in Vacaville, Solano County, California (38.306, −121.825) at 6.5 m elevation. The colony nested in a 7.0-ha, water-managed pond containing tule covering approximately 25% of the pond. The colony is surrounded by agricultural land and grassland on the eastern, western, and southern borders and a landfill on the northern border. A heavily traveled highway borders the eastern edge.

column78: The first nesting attempt was in the northeast corner of the pond and was about 150m from the ARU, whereas the second nesting attempt was much closer and was in the west part of the pond. There are also a lot of Red-winged Blackbird calls, and the Pattern Matching jobs located these Red-winged Blackbird Female Chatter more readily than the Tricolored Blackbird Female Chatter, as the Red-winged Blackbirds were much closer to the ARU. I was very conservative when annotating the presence of Tricolored Blackbird Female Chatter, and only located 20 of them. There is a small nesting attempt that begins in April, and a handful of Fledgling Begging Calls can be heard on 17-20 May, though no other begging calls were detected, possibly due to the distance from the ARU. A second nesting attempt started in May which was much closer to the ARU and resulted in more detectable Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls. This second attempt also barely skirted the effects of the strom that was several days before onset of Brooding. NOTE - I have detailed notes from regular site visits.
column84: Small triangular pond bordered by road on the north and west sides, and a train track along the southeast side. Construction of the roads was under way during the breeding season. The first nesting attempt was in the far northeast corner and was about 150m from the recorder. The second was 50m.

column78: Female Chatter, Nestling Begging Calls, and Fledgling Begging Calls overlapped broadly, producing an extended period of mixed-stage vocalizations characteristic of asynchronous nesting. Although automated detection undercounted Female Chatter due to masking by Male Chorus and later-stage Begging Calls, manual evaluation showed continuous presence of chatter throughout the Brooding period. Abundant Fledgling Begging Calls confirmed successful reproduction.

column78: Male Chrous started in earnest in mid March, but females were not recruited until May. At approximately the time eggs would have been hatching there was a rain storm (mid-May), and the site was abandoned. Also noted signs of predation along edge of pond, and watched a NOHA hunt and eat one of the birds. Note - this is the same storm that likely caused the Denverton Creek colony abandonment. Note - I have extensive field notes.

column78: Acoustic evidence showed strong early activity consistent with brood initiation, followed by a sharp decline shortly after the onset of Brooding. A small number of birds continued nesting and successfully fledged a limited number of young, but overall activity diminished rapidly. Sparse detections of Begging Calls suggest that most of the colony abandoned the nesting attempt. Several days of rain occurred during the incubation period and may have contributed to the partial abandonment.

column78: Although the colony was very large and located at some distance from the recorder, Fledgling Begging Calls were consistently detected, confirming successful reproduction. Pattern matching identified the louder vocalizations, while weaker early-stage calls required manual review to confirm the presence of Female Chatter. Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls were faint but a handful were detected, and the overall acoustic pattern reflected a single synchronous nesting attempt.

column78: The ARU was placed distant from the main part of the colony, so most of the vocalizations were very faint. A few nests were close to the ARU, allowing for accurate analysis of timing of vocalizations for at least this segment of the colony. The earliest Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls were not picked up by the pattern matching jobs, but a manual analysis for Hatchling Begging Calls allowed for estimation of onset of Brooding. Fledgling Begging Calls, being much louder, were detected by the pattern matching jobs, allowing for estimation of Fledging and Dispersal dates.
column80: The ARU was placed distant from the main part of the colony, so most of the vocalizations were very faint. This made evaluation of Male Chorus tricky. A few nests were close to the ARU, allowing for analysis of timing of vocalizations. The earliest vocalizations of both the hatchlings and nestlings were not picked up by the pattern matching jobs, likely due to them being faint in the recordings, but a manual analysis for Hatchling Begging Calls allowed for estimation of hatching date. Fledgling Begging Calls, being much louder, were detected by the pattern matching jobs, allowing for estimation of fledging and dispersal dates.

column78:
A colony established at this sedge-lined pond and initiated a breeding attempt in early April. Male Chorus and Female Chatter were detected consistently, followed by the appearance of Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls, confirming that eggs hatched. However, the ARU batteries failed before Fledgling Begging Calls could be documented, preventing determination of whether young fledged.
Because the deployment ended before the key transition between Brooding and Fledging, the structure of the attempt and the colony’s outcome remain Unknown.

column78: The ARU was too far from the birds for robust pattern matching analysis. Both Female Chatter and Nestling Begging Call had very few validations, and Hatchling Begging Call had zero. This is likely due to the recorder being too distant from the colony to pick up these fainter vocalizations. To better understand the timing of these fainter vocalizations both a mini-manual analysis and a more complete manual analysis of the recordings were completed. All results are consistent with each other.
column80: The ARU was too far from the birds for robust pattern matching analysis. Both Female Chatter and Nestling Begging Call had very few validations, and Hatchling Begging Call had zero. Hatchling Begging Calls were located through manual review of recordings. Completed a mini-manual analysis as well as an intensive manual analysis by listening to six recordings from each day. All results are consistent with each other.

column78: The ARU was placed after Male Chorus started. The fainter vocalizations of Female Chatter, Hatchling Begging Calls, and the youngest Nestling Begging Calls were not picked up well using the pattern matching jobs, presumably due to the distance of the colony from the ARU. Because of this I performed a mini-manual analysis, which agreed with the sparse results from the pattern matching.
column80: The ARU was placed after Male Chorus started. The fainter vocalizations of Female Chatter, Hatchling Begging Calls, and the youngest Nestling Begging Calls were not picked up well using the pattern matching jobs. Because of this I performed a mini-manual analysis  where I listened to eight recordings every third day and annotated the presence of the six vocalizations of interest. Note Hatchling, Nestling, and Fledgling Begging Calls are lumped together in mini-manual analysis.

column78: There were two bouts of breeding, with the first bout being more robust than the first, as evidenced by the abundance of the vocalizations. The second bout has consistent, but less abundant Female Chatter. The ARU was retrieved shortly after the Hatchling Begging Calls from the second bout of breeding are heard. Successful fledging of this weak second bout of breeding cannot be determined because ARU was removed prior to expected fledging date. NOTE-THERE IS A MANUAL ANALYSIS WITH THE WRONG TAG (reviewed-WS-e) THAT HAS BEEN FIXED TO GET MANUAL GRAPHING TO WORK. TO GRAPH CORRECTLY WILL NEED TO REDOWNLOAD EXCEL FROM ARBIMON.
column80: The first bout of breeding had some asynchrony, demonstrated bythe presence of Female Chatter for seven days after the onset of Brooding. There is also evidence of a Replacement bout of breeding, though the amount of Female Chatter is very minimal, and if the breeding attempt existed beyond the date the ARU was pulled, would have resulted in only a small number of nests. The ARU was retrieved on approximately the date this second weak Replacement bout of eggs would have hatched. If the 2nd breeding bout had been productive, I estimate that Incubating started on approximately 30-May (end of Male Chorus), and Brooding started on approximately 10-Jun, and fledging on approximately 24-Jun. NOTE-THERE IS A MANUAL ANALYSIS WITH THE WRONG TAG (reviewed-WS-e) THAT NEEDS TO BE FIXED TO GET MANUAL GRAPHING TO WORK. WE CAN DO THIS WITH A SEARCH AND REPLACE IN THE CORRECT EXCEL SHEET. ITS ONLY 400 OR SO TAGS AND WOULD BE QUICK TO CLEAN UP. TO GRAPH CORRECTLY WILL NEED TO REDOWNLOAD EXCEL FROM ARBIMON.

column79:
This deployment is considered a duplicate dataset of 2021 Willey Wetlands 3. 
The ARU was placed at the periphery of an extensive wetland that also hosted a large White-faced Ibis colony. TRBL vocalizations were present but often faint, and female and early nestling calls were partially masked. Despite this, a clear progression from Nestling to Fledgling Begging Calls indicated successful reproduction. A decline in detections on 7 July coincided with dispersal dates observed in adjacent ARUs and suggests that birds near this recorder represented a slightly later portion of the larger colony.
column80: Manually analyzed data. Large Ibis colony very loud. Recorder appears to be a little distant to where the Tricolored Blackbirds are, but I can her the vocalizations. Many are too faint for template analysis, so a mini manual, followed by edge analysis was performed. Recorder was placed after settlement. Somewhere around when they fail you can hear what I believe might be the other part of the colony right as they are about to fledge. I also think I hear a lot of EUST around this time. There were lots of nestlings up until about 7/6-7/7. Then there is just one or two that hang on. I am calling it a failure at the 7/7ish date. Interestingly this is the date that the other two colonies fledged. My take is that this area was a late attempt compared to the other two areas. And that the majority of the nestlings were old enough to join the crowd when the rest of the colony left the area. Template worked marginally for MS and NC and did not work at all for FS.FS couldn't be located using template analysis. Did mark presence of Female Song when reviewing recordings, so last date here is from these manually reviewed recordings. Recorder was placed just before hatching date, so no Male Chorus. Manual analysis.

column78: Something did not work. Initially the ARU was placed in a plastic baggie, and audio of Male Song can be detected. I then shipped a drybox to them and when the recorder was placed into it the recordings became extremely faint, and unusable. This was the first drybox we used, and we were not aware that it was critical that the microphone be placed near the acoustic membrane. I suspect that the ARU was placed in the drybox in such a way that the microphone was not over the acoustic membrane. Though vocalizations are extemely faint, a mini-manual analysis was able to detect both Male Chorus and Nestling and Fledgling Begging Calls. Based on this, onset of Brooding was ~9-May and since I hear Fledglings, the colony was successful. A complete manual analysis of the site might result in more confident dates and categorization of the colony.
column80: Something did not work. Either the recorder is too distant, the recorder was placed backwards in the drybox, or the microphone failed. I can barely hear the chorus, but all other vocalizations are not distinguishable, so no analysis was performed.

column78: Only scattered detections of Male Song were recorded, and neither Female Chatter nor Begging Calls were present. A mini manual review confirmed this lack of vocalization detection. These acoustic patterns indicate that birds visited the site but did not initiate breeding. Field observations noted nesting activity prior to ARU placement, but by the time recording began, only a few males remained, consistent with the absence of colony formation.
column80: AudioMoth "H", 2 weeks prior to placement of the recorder the site had a lot of Tricolored Blackbirds (audio recording 4/29/2021 10:28). Email from Amy "4/14/2021: "On 4/12/2021 I observed nesting behavior at one of our CNLM preserves in Alameda County.  There were about 100 birds; some of them were carrying nesting material in their beaks". Only one Tricolored Blackbird seen at time of deployment (audio recording 4/29/2021 10:28). Email from Amy 7/14/2021: "I'm afraid this site probably didn't pan out for our Tricolored Blackbird after all, sadly.  When I deployed, there were over 100 trikes, but by the second visit they had decamped and only a dozen remained, then finally only one lonely male who was getting chased off the marsh by RWBBs."
column84: Site is an approx. 4500 sq. meter (1.2 acre) stock pond within a ~400 acre grassland matrix that also hosts California red-legged frog, California tiger salamander, and seasonal waterfowl. Surrounding land uses are ranching and horse boarding. There is a shooting range nearby (you may hear shots). I noted about 100 Tricolored Blackbirds at the pond April 12. Unfortunately when I returned to place the recorder, they appear to have been supplanted by Red-winged Blackbirds. I observed one male Tricolored Blackbird that was chased off the pond by a male Red-winged Blackbird a few times.

There were about 100 birds; some of them were carrying nesting material in their beaks". Only one Tricolored Blackbird seen at time of deployment (audio recording 4/29/2021 10:28). When I deployed, there were over 100 trikes, but by the second visit they had decamped and only a dozen remained, then finally only one lonely male who was getting chased off the marsh by RWBBs."

column78: Male Song and Male Chorus were readily detected, while Female Chatter and early nestling calls were faint. Manual review revealed multiple Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls over a sustained period, consistent with normal Brooding. Although Fledgling Begging Calls were not detected, the presence of Nestling Begging Calls were detected for greater than 14 days, it is assumed the young fledged and immediately dispersed.
column80: Really really small. Only a few vocalizations noted. Nestling never gets to a full fledged Call. Nestling is heard for 14 days, so assumed to have successfully fledged, But if it did stick around I hear zero fledgling calls. But with the lack of numbers I wonder if this would actually be what would happen. THat is if there is one Fledgling, with no one else to hang out with, you might disperse immediately. Required manual of core. Very small number. Dates are estimates due to scarcity of recordings with vocalizations. Because of this very intermittent vocalizations. Uncertain if the one/couple of nestlings that I do hear made it to fledging. Male chorus was difficult to analyze, I think I might be picking up the adjacent large colony that settled at 27-2 and then largely abandoned. The large colony arrived on 10-May at 7pm.
column84: Both T27.1 and T27.2 were converted from fallow rice to wetland in 2013 and managed as seasonal wetland until 2014.  In 2015 were put into a long-term permanent/semi-permanent rotation as part of a Giant Garter Snake program, and in 2016 the first Tricolored Blackbird colony was recorded, and has occurred in one of the two ponds each year since.  Pond management includes winter overwater prescribed fire, sheep grazing (they will be detected on the audio recording), and mowing/disking.  Additional details are available upon request.
column86: Jennifer Isola, Michael Derrico, Mike Carpenter

column78: Male Song and Male Chorus increased in mid-May, followed by limited Female Chatter, indicating poor recruitment. The recorder failed shortly after the onset of Brooding, preventing determination of either colony type or outcome. Colony type and outcome remain Unknown because the ARU failed shortly after Brooding began.
column80: Required manual of core data. Large group showed for settling, but only a handful stayed for nesting. There are a couple of male songs before the settling that I have confirmed are real. Battery failed just days after hatching. Could not confirm successful fledging

column78: While the bulk of the breecding was Simple, there are a few Nestling Begging Calls that extend beyond when the Fledglings disperse, indicating that there was some Aysynchronous breeding at this site.
column84: Multiple blackberry brambles interspersed with cattails and bulrushes exist along the creek west of the road. Four brambles are colony locations, 60-200 yards from parkway, each along the canal

column78: Acoustic detections showed a clean, synchronous nesting bout with well-defined transitions between vocalization stages. One continuous sequence of Begging Calls led into a predictable Fledging pulse, with no evidence of a second cohort or disturbance.
column84: The Panoche Creek Marsh consists of six miles of brackish perennial surface water, originating in the western part of Silver Creek Ranch, and flowing for about 6 miles through the Preserve and adjacent BLM land, before disappearing into the sandy soils on the western edge of the San Joaquin Valley. The first mile of this wetland consists of a narrow stream which flows through riparian woodland dominated by phreatophytic plants including Fremont Cottonwood and red willow, and herbaceous understory plants such as salt grass  and alkali heath. The stream then broadens into an emergent marsh dominated by narrow-leaf cattail  and bulrush. The Tricolored Blackbird colonies in 2021 occurred primarily along the western half of this wetland. A prescribed burn was conducted in this area on February 7th, 2020.

column78: A clear burst of Settlement activity occurred early in the deployment, followed by a sharp reduction in vocalizations as most birds left the area. A small number of birds remained and successfully fledged young, producing a faint but distinct pulse of Fledgling Begging Calls. Reduced abundance and compressed Brooding and Fledging signatures are consistent with Partial Abandonment.
column84: The Panoche Creek Marsh consists of six miles of brackish perennial surface water, originating in the western part of Silver Creek Ranch, and flowing for about 6 miles through the Preserve and adjacent BLM land, before disappearing into the sandy soils on the western edge of the San Joaquin Valley. column92: 2021 Panoche Creek Preserve 2 East: These were definitely in the same colony. 1E had much better data

column78: There are two nesting attempts with the second nesting attempt starting about 23 days after the first. The second nesting attempt in a colony undergoing Multiple nesting attempts is typically more than 28 days after the onset of the first nesting attempt, and commencing when the fledglings have left. This particular case is unusual, in that it is significantly shorter than the 28 day spacing, and likely nestlings are still in the nest from the first wave of breeding. This could be explained if instead of a second nesting attempt, there was a different set of birds that arrived as an Addition which took up unused portions of the breeding substrate. I have field notes for this site collected by Chris Conrad (passed along to me by Deren Ross), and they are consistent an Addition.
column80: Pulse one over laps pulse 2, such that the YNC of pulse 2 over lap with ONC of pulse 1. There is a drop in ONC starting the 25th, suggesting that a group dispersed on this date. Edge analysis of the first pulse shows evidence of a possible weak pulse before this first one that is recorded. The second pulse has YNC starting consistently on 5/24. Cleaned up the NC templates to better stick with the age range by insisting that the sonogrms more closely look like the template. Hear a consistent but very infrequent nestling call all the way to start (need to finish going back in time on edge to prove this is true)
column84: The site consists of several adjacent clumps of Himalayan Blackberry just east of Industrial Avenue, about 1/4 mile south of Twelve Bridges Rd.

column78: This deployment is considered a duplicate dataset of 2021 Willey Wetlands 3.
column79:
This deployment is considered a duplicate dataset of 2021 Willey Wetlands 3.  
Despite substantial background noise from ibis, all TRBL vocalizations were detected reliably. The ARU captured the onset of Brooding and produced a strong, uninterrupted sequence of Begging Calls through Fledging. This site displayed a typical synchronous nesting attempt.

column78: This deployment is considered the core dataset for the Willey Wetlands group as it provided the most robust detections. Pattern matching for all six vocalizations worked well at this site despite the background of nesting ibis. ARU was placed during the incubation phase and captured the very first Hatchling Begging Calls.
column80: Dispersal day was 7/5-7/6 there were a few nestlings that lingered past this date. I marked 6/21/2021 as last Female Song as I located some during manual analysis of nestling call. I relyed on this because template for Female found very few recordings with Female Song present.
column84: Recorder is placed at the edge of a perennial wetland that was created for the benefit of Giant Garter Snakes.  The record is facing west, across a wide channel, towards a colony in thick tules and cattails which is also being occupied by a very large White-faced Ibis colony, with the Tricolored Blackbird diffusely spread throughout the area.  Recorded placed where a more dense concentration of Tricolored Blackbird were observed, but perhaps only a few hundred at this location.  This recorder is on the southern side of this particular colony.

column78: Only a handful of Male Song detected. A mini-manual analysis was performed to confirm lack of Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations.
column80: Manual
column84: Patch of cattails about 70 m long x 8 m wide, along a water channel in a mixed pasture/marsh. The patch is 40 m west of city road. The birds "share" the patch with Red-winged Blackbird, BHCO, GTGR, and EUST (looks like the EUST use the patch only for roosting).

column78: Only a handful of scattered recordings with Male Song and Male Chorus. Colony never formed. A mini-manual analysis confirms the pattern matching results. Note - I have Meredith's field visit notes in Sheets.
column84: The colony nested in a 0.9-ha, stream-fed pond containing cattails and bulrushes , together covering approximately 60% of the pond. Grassland, which is grazed by cattle, surrounds the site.

column78: Colony appears to be very small and produced not detections of Female Chatter or Hatchling, Nestling, or Fledgling Begging Calls. Because of this first a min-manual and then a more thorough manual were done, and a handful of begging calls were located which extend long enough to suggest that the few young produced at this site successfully fledged.  Due to the scarcity of vocalizations reported dates are very apporximate.
column80: Manual, due to the scarceity of vocalizations reported dates are very apporximate. There are more manually analyzed recordings than in the graphs. They are tagged "reviewed-WS". Also called hatch day for the colony with only 2 rec=present due to small size of the colony. There were 2 recordings with Male Chorus that are timed correctly with Onset of Incubation, so I am using these as the dates. With more manual analysis by listening to more recordings I might be able to firm this up, but only do after all others. So few birds there was never a male chorus mid-day. There were a couple of mornings with Male Chorus at 8am.
column84: Natural riparian forest, the Tricolored Blackbird colony is located in a patch of mulefat and Stinging Nettle. The colony is surrounded by red willows in the north and west, and by a pasture to the east. The recorder was placed on a T-post in an opening adjacent to the colony at 2 m high.

column78: Only a handful of Male Song detected. A mini-manual analysis was performed to confirm lack of Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations.

column84: Bulrush pond surrounded by red willows at south, southwest, north, northeast, and east. Surrounded by rabbitbrush at west and northwest. Adjacent to the rabbitbrush, there are large Fremont Cottonwood trees, 20 m tall.

column78: Colony abandoned on 14-May.  The ARU was pulled 20-May for reuse at another site. There was no obvious reason for the abandonment. Mini-manual analysis detected a single recording which has a potential Tricolored Blackbird nestling vocalization. The ARU was redeployed at the much larger colony at Conaway Ranch.
column80: Colony abandoned on 14-May.  Recorder was pulled 20-May for reuse at another site. There were three consecutive days of temperatures above 90 from 11 May to 13 May which could be the reason for abandonment. There is a single recording which has a potential Tricolored Blackbird nestling vocalization, though it is brief, and I am not certain that it is truly a Tricolored Blackbird nestling. Also, there is a Red-winged Blackbird adult in this recording as well, so it could just be a Red-winged Blackbird nestling. ARU was redeployed at Conaway Ranch.

column78: The ARU was placed after Male Chorus had started. Vocalizations were picked up very well, including Hatchling Begging Calls. This is one of a few sites where Hatchling Begging Calls were easily detected and these recordings could prove useful for a deeper analysis of the earliest vocalizations. NOTE - MINI MANUAL TAGS WERE REMOVED. SHOULD GO AWAY UPON REQUEST FOR NEW EXCEL FROM ARBIMON.
column80: The ARU was placed after Male Chorus had started. Fledgling Begging Calls are not present for the entire day starting June 30th, so I have marked fledging day as June 29th, though there are a few fledglings in the recordings through July 2nd. NOTE - REMOVE MINI MANUAL TAGS HERE. THEY WERE NOT COMPLETE, AND THE ANALYSIS IS NOT NEEDED. WE AN DO THIS BY DELETING THE TAG IN THE EXCEL SHEET WE GOT FROM ARBIMON.

column78: The ARU was placed right at the end of Male Chorus. Based on the density of vocalizations in the recordings this was a very small colony. The ARU was pulled on the day after the first Hatchling Begging Calls were heard, and there are only 23 recordings found with Hatchling Begging Calls. While this site was largely abandoned, we cannot be certain if the hatchlings heard survived to fledging, or if the site was abandoned altogether. The ARU was redeployed at the much larger colony at Conaway Ranch.

column78: This was an extremely small colony. The dates are extremely rough and based on just a few recordings which contained Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations. column80: Manual. This colony was extremely small. The dates are extremely rough and based on just a few recordings which contained Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations. Male Chorus was never robust. I set hatch date for the colony based on last Female Song. Tagged recordings failed to detect the youngest nestlings. However I did loacte a few that I am certain of on 5/8 and 5/10.
column84: The colony is in a patch of Stinging Nettle (old and new), next to a young patch of skinny Fremont Cottonwoods in the north, and next to a pasture in the south. The recorder was placed in a cottonwood at 2.2 m high. The land is owned by Audubon Kern River Preserve.

column78: Female Chatter was detected briefly early in the deployment, indicating initiation of nest building. Vocalizations declined sharply soon afterward, and no Begging Calls were recorded. The rapid loss of vocal activity indicates that breeding was abandoned shortly after initiation. The cause of abandonment could not be determined acoustically.
column80: Abandoned, battery ran out on last days so just spot checked on recordings I did have to confirm lack of presence, males were showing up off and on starting in Feb, so I didn't have to do all as edge I cherry picked recordings with the MC present, these are just marked as reviewed-WS. Females only sang for a couple of days before colony abandoned. There were isolated Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations after 4/22/2021, but these were scarce after 4/22.
column84: Tricolored Blackbirds nested in a 0.2-ha patch of Himalayan Blackberry in a small area designated as open space surrounded by roadways, commercial stores, parking lots, and a housing development

column84: The nesting colony used several patches of Himalayan Blackberry, totaling approximately 0.6 ha, along Markham Ravine Creek. The site was surrounded by cultivated rice fields, open grassland, and a former irrigated hayfield that was converted to a wetland mitigation site during 2018.
column87: no longer there, email Charlotte Marks instead

column78: This is a Complex colony that exhibits traits of both an Asynchronous colony that also had Multiple nesting attempts. Female Chatter which continues for a long time after first Hatchling Begging Calls are heard, as one would expect in an Asynchronous colony. However, the presence of two distinct bouts of Fledgling Begging Calls shows the a replacement nesting attempt. There is also detectable Hatchling Begging Calls at two distinct times as well as a pooling of the frequency of Nestling Begging Calls into two bouts.
column80: Asynchronous, if there was Male Chorus it was before recorder was placed. Appears to be a continuosly nesting colony in that there is no pulsing to the Female Song and Female Song continues for a long time after fisrst hatchlings are heard. There are two rounds of fledgling dispersal. One on 6/1 and the other on 6/16. Of course uncertain if the gap is caused by the creche leaving and returning or if it is a second group of late hatchers that make up the second pulse of Fledglings.
column84: The colony of Tricolored Blackbird is in a himalayan blackberry bush, 20 m long x 5 m wide, adjacent to a paved highway. (in a public right of way). There is a water channel and pasture (with cows present) adjacent to the blackberry bush to the north. The recorder was placed inside the colony, on the east side, at 1 m high. The recorder will pick up significant road noise at this site.

column78: No Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations detected. To confirm this I did a mini-manual analysis. I accidentlly reviewed three recordings from every day rather than every third.
column80: Manual, accidentlly did every day rather than every third
column84: Small pond with dormant cattails. The landowner mentioned raccoon predators in previous years; no Tricolored Blackbird present when unit was deployed. The landowner is James McCutcheon, email gwschool@wildblue.net

column78: This was a small colony and there were only a handful of detections in the pattern matching jobs. To confirm the results from the pattern matching I performed a mini-manual analysis, but accidentally did three recordings every day, rather than every three. Mini-manual and pattern matching results agree, and all Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations cease on 4-Jun.
column80: If there was Male Chorus it was before recorder was placed. Hatch day for colony only had 5 rec w/ YNC present, but since this was a small colony I accepted a smaller number of present to indicate hatch day. Colony failed and last Tricolored Blackbird vocalization was heard on 6/5/2021.
column84: Riparian forest composed of old Fremont Cottonwood and red willow trees and many young Fremont Cottonwood trees (< 3 m tall). The ground is covered mainly by grass (Alkali rye) with many patches of dead and new Stinging Nettle. There are also some areas with mulefat. the colony is Tricolored Blackbird is ~60 m from an irrigation channel and ~100 m from the South Fork Kern River. Colony area is owned by Audubon Kern River Preserve, but not open to the public.

column78: The first recordings from the ARU have Female Chatter, Fledgling, and Hatchling Begging Calls. Only a few Hatchling Begging Calls were located, but there are many Fledgling Begging Calls. Because of this, I believe that the Fledglings are from an earlier attempt, and that there was an Asynchronous nesting attempt that is the source of the Hatchling Begging Calls.  Because I only have the tail end of the nesting attempt, I do not know the breeding form of the colony, but I suspect Asynchronous because of the Female Chatter and Hatchling Begging Calls that are overlapping the Fledgling Begging Calls. This suggests that both Brooding and Dispersal are occurring simultaneously, consistent with an Asynchronous colony. The Fledglings Dispersed on 31-May, after which only two Fledgling Begging Calls are detected. It is possible that these two Fledgling Begging Calls are coming from the Aysnchonous hatchlings heard earlier in the recordings.
column80: Very small colony, needed manual analysis. Hear fledglings at the beginning, so appears that this was placed after a successful first round. Because of this I have marked the pulse that has hatchlings as pulse 2. There are very few vocalizations, and the last nestling call I hear is on 6/9/2022. These vocalizations are distant to the recorder, and don't quite sound like fledglings. Because of this, I can't be certain that the young from this second pulse successfully fledged, though their vocalizations are heard 13 days after initial hatchling calls are heard, so I suspect that they did.
column83: Bulrush or tule, Cattails, Common Reed
column84: Wetland complex on private agricultural and ranch lands surrounded by levee road. Tricolored Blackbirds were first detected in WA in 1998. In 1999, a bird was detected near this site, and the location has had regular reports most years since. It is unclear if anyone had located this colony prior to my efforts this year, or for how long this actual colony site has been used. It seems they have nested in the area somewhere and somewhat regularly since colonizing Washington.
column88: Audio on 5/27/2022 confirms time and location as Harder Springs. No email notes.

column78: ARU was set for 1 every 10 min, thus it ran out of battery mid season. A few Male Song were detected, but no other Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations were detected. So either no colony formed or if the colony did form it was too distant and or too small to be detected by the ARU.
column80: Recorder was set for 1 every 10 min, thus it ran out of battery mid season. A few male song were detected, but no other Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations were detected. So either no colony formed or if the colony did form it was too distant and or too small to be detected by the ARU.
column83: Bulrush or tule, Cattails, Himalayan Blackberry
column84: Strapped to a fence post bordering the colony.  Ten feet off a country road

column78: Each of the two nesting attempts has some asynchrony. Female Chatter isn't detected prior to the hatching of the second bout of eggs, possibly because of the background vocalizations of the asynchronous colony drowning them out.
column80: Colony is all over the place, but I am documenting the 2 pulses that seem the most prevalent. The first pulse isn't large. The Dispersal date was assigned because I noted a couple of recordngs with much higher density of Fledgling calls, so a little spike. I marked the highes t density recording with the tage Fledgling Dispersal. I still need to analyze the second pulse. I believe that there are two asynchronous pulses. The first HD 4/12-4/15, the second HD ~<5/22/-6/1. Or it is a continuously laying colony.
column84: The Hay Landfill colony site is in a mitigation pond adjacent to the Hay Road Landfill in Vacaville, Solano County, California (38.306, −121.825) at 6.5 m elevation. The colony nested in a 7.0-ha, water-managed pond containing tule covering approximately 25% of the pond. The colony is surrounded by agricultural land and grassland on the eastern, western, and southern borders and a landfill on the northern border. A heavily traveled highway borders the eastern edge.

column78: After the first birds establish a nesting attempt, a larger group joins them about 21 days later, resulting in overlapping breeding stages. Onset of Brooding for the first nesting attempt is roughly determined as the Male Chorus from the Addition drowns out the Hatchling Begging Calls. The fledgling Dispersal date of the first nesting attempt is also an estimate as the Nestling Begging Calls from the Addition make it hard to determine the exact date. Most of the Fledglings from the Addition disperse on 21-Jun, but stragglers can be heard thru the end of the recordings. Battery started running out on 4-Jul and completely died by 13-Jul.
column80: Sub-colony addition. After the first birds established a larger group appears to have joined them, resulting in overlapping breeding stages.  Based on density of nestling calls the second addition of birds was significanly larger than the first. The hatching date for the colony for pulse 1 is estimated, as the onset of pulse 2 Male Chorus drowns out the nestlings. So dates marked as nestling call not present when there is the loud male chorus are likely just because I can't hear them. When I do finally hear them, it is obvious that they are older nestlings. A few nestlings were heard on 5/17, and with most colonies the majority of hatching happens the day after first nestlings are heard, so I estimate that hatching date is ~5/18. The Fledgling dispersal date of pulse 1 is also an estimate as the calls from pulse 2 nestlings make it hard to determine the exact date. For recordings that were analyzed to determine the edge of hatching and dispersal (p1n, p2n) where the two pulaes overlapped I have marked the YNC with the tag YNC-p2 and the older nestling calls with ONC-p1 to distinguish between the two pulses of nestlings. I picked the p1 dispersal date on the day that seemed to have a lull in the ONC. There is a temporary lull in p2 nestling calls 6/12-6/13. There was also a rain storm on that day which maybe explains the lull. The majority of the nestlings disperse on 7/3/2022 (last day with high volume of NCs), but stragglers can be heard thru the end of the recordings. Battery started running out on July 4th and completely died by July 13th.
column84: Isolated pond/spring are approximately 2 acres in size, likely natural spring plus irrigation water. Some open water but mainly mix of Common Reed, bulrush, and cattail. First discovered in 2018 (but could have existed long before) and used each year since.

column78:
A colony of approximately 200 birds established at the site in March. Acoustic evidence indicated two distinct and complete breeding attempts. The first attempt was the larger of the two; it was characterized by high densities of Female Chatter, strong Nestling Begging Calls, and a broad period of Fledgling Begging Calls prior to Dispersal.

After fledglings from the first attempt dispersed, a second, smaller attempt began. Male Chorus again intensified, Female Chatter resumed, and a full sequence of Hatchling, Nestling, and Fledgling Begging Calls followed. Both attempts concluded with successful fledging, and no disturbances were detected during the season.

column78: Nestlings are detected on the very first day that the ARU was placed. This site had continuous Male Chorus, suggesting asynchronous of colony formation. However, there is also a hint that there is a Repeating bout of breeding in that there are two bouts of Fledgling Begging Calls that are spaced approximately 30 days apart. From the density of detections, it appears that the second bout of breeding was larger than the first bout. Due to the background of Asynchronous breeding obscuring vocalizations of the second bout of breeding, breeding stage dates for the second bout were not determined and dates reported are for the colony as a whole. Note ARU was set to record one minute out of every ten.

column84: Audio Moth #60 was deployed on a levee road between Tract 27.2 and Tract 27.1 of Colusa National Wildlife Refuge (NWR), just north of the 2021 colony that lies within T27.2.  Both T27.1 and T27.2 were converted from fallow rice to wetland in 2013 and managed as seasonal wetland until 2014.  In 2015 were put into a long-term permanent/semi-permanent rotation as part of a Giant Garter Snake program, and in 2016 the first Tricolored Blackbird colony was recorded, and has occurred in one of the two ponds each year since.  Pond management includes winter overwater prescribed fire, sheep grazing (they will be detected on the audio recording), and mowing/disking.  Additional details are available upon request.

column78: ARU either ran out of battery or was pulled before Fledglings dispersed. ARU was programmed for 1 min every 10, possibly explaining why batteries potentially failed before the end of the season. Colony was too small to generate a Male Chorus. Onset of Brooding is extremely tenuous as there are only a handful of recordings detected with Hatchling Begging Calls. I have one recording with Hatchling Begging Call on 16-May that I am convinced of, and several others around this time that are likely Hatchling Begging Calls. column80: Recorder either ran out of battery or was pulled before nestlings fledged. Colony was too small to generate a male chorus, so incubation onset will need to be estimated at 11 days before hatch day. Unkown if nestlings survived to fledging as recordings stopped when they were only ~8 days old. There is a hint that there may have been an earlier attempt. I have one recording with YNC on 5/16/2022 and there is also a weak FS bout that correlates with this as well as a couple of FCs that imply a fledging date od 5/30. So I am betting that there was actually pulse 1 with hatch day before 5/16 and that these young fledged somewhere around/before 5/30. And there is a second round hatching around 5/27 and these would have fledged after the recordngs stopped. If this is the case, then this suggests a sub colony addition. Unfortunately the recordings re so faint that I cannot be sure.

Because I likely missed the first days of Hatchling Begging Calls due to them being too faint, it is assumed that this second nesting attempt also successfully fledged and dispersed without being detected on the recordings. column78: The density of Female Chatter drops sharply on 20-May, suggesting Partial Abandonment on that date. Based on the density of vocalizations on Begging Calls in recordings, there were only a small number of nests that continued beyond this date. There was a large increase in the number of recordings with Fledgling Begging Calls on 12-Jun, so while the pattern matching is spotty for Begging Calls, I am certain that the small number of remaining active nests successfully fledged young.  There were three days of 90F+ from 17 May to 19 May which may have contributed to the Partial Abandonment.
column80: Based on the density of vocalizations in recordings, there were a small number of nests near this recorder, and there was no robust detection of Nestling or early Fledgling Begging Calls. Interestingly, the density of Female Chatter drops sharply, and I wonder if this suggests that the majority of females chose not to nest at this location and abandoned. There was a large increase in the number of recordings with Fledgling Begging Calls on June 12, so while the pattern matching is spotty, I am certain that the small number of nests close to this ARU successfully fledged young.

column78: A colony of Tricolored Blackbirds established at this site and completed a successful breeding attempt in Himalayan Blackberry. The colony was moderately small, with an estimated 400–500 birds. Nestling Begging Calls were already present in the first recordings, indicating that one nesting attempt was well underway before the ARU was deployed. Hatchling Begging Calls appeared later in the recording period, showing that an additional nesting attempt occurred while the recorder was active. Because the first attempt began before the ARU was in place, the acoustic record cannot distinguish whether the colony’s structure reflects an Addition to the original attempt or Asynchronous nesting. Fledgling Begging Calls developed before the end of the deployment, confirming that the colony produced fledglings successfully.
column79: A colony of Tricolored Blackbirds established at this site and completed a successful breeding attempt in Himalayan Blackberry. The colony was moderately large, with an estimated 400–500 birds. Nestling Begging Calls were already present in the first recordings, indicating that one nesting attempt was well underway before the ARU was deployed. Hatchling Begging Calls appeared later in the recording period, showing that an additional nesting attempt occurred while the recorder was active. Because the first attempt began before the ARU was in place, the acoustic record cannot distinguish whether the colony’s structure reflects an Addition to the original attempt or Asynchronous nesting among subgroups. Fledgling Begging Calls developed before the end of the deployment, confirming that the colony produced fledglings successfully.

column78: Recording quality at this site was low, with faint detections limiting resolution of early-stage vocalizations such as Female Chatter. However, Fledgling Begging Calls were consistently detectable and revealed four distinct pulses of fledglings. The approximately month-long spacing between pulses is consistent with a Multiple colony structure. Because early-stage vocalizations were poorly resolved, confidence in distinguishing Multiple from Asynchronous patterns is reduced, but available evidence supports classification as Multiple. All attempts produced fledglings.
column79:
The ARU didn't pick up the colony very well and all vocalizations are quite faint. Female Chatter is never heard, but there is almost continuous Male Chorus, and I can barely hear the young. Fledgling Begging Calls, being more strident, were picked up by the ARUs, and analysis of the Fledgling Begging Calls suggests there were two successful bouts of breeding, with the first bout starting with a small group which then had a larger Addition. This lead to the presence of Fledling Begging Calls from 1-May to 6-May (weak first bout), 22-May to 5-Jun (stronger Addition), and 21-Jun tp 24-Jun (Repeat). If this is correct, I can estimate the breeding stages as Bout #1: Incubation started ~6-Apr, Brooding ~16-Apr, and confirmed to have Fledged on 1-May and Dispersed 6-May. There was an addition to this first bout, with this addition starting to Incubate ~28-Apr, Brooding ~8-May, and was confirmed to have Fledged on 22-May and these fledglings hung around until 5-Jun. Once this first bout was completed, a Repeat bout was initiated and Incubation began ~27-May, Brooding ~7-Jun, and Fledging on 21-Jun and stuck around until 24-Jun, after which the majority of the Fledgling Begging Calls cease. There is a long tail of occasional Fledgling Begging Calls that extends through 27-Jul. I do not know if these are stragglers finishing up a really late breeding attempt, or if these are just fledglings that are re-visiting the area occasionally. Mini Manual was completed. 

ISSUE #1: None of the other results that I've reviewed are explicit about restating the dates like this. There's Table 4 in Results that have all the same information. It seems like either all of the sites should have this restated, or none should. 
ISSUE #2: The dates here are different than what's in Table 4. e.g. Table 4 has FBC from 24-May to 5-Jun, above it says 22-May to 5-Jun. Above says Incubation started 6-Apr, 28-Apr, and 27-May, but the table says Before, ND, and ND.

Some alternate wording for the first part: 
The ARU captured the colony poorly, and all vocalizations were faint. Female Chatter never occurred in the recordings, but Male Chorus was nearly continuous, and only faint vocalizations from young were audible. Fledgling Begging Calls, being more strident, carried into the recordings, and their timing suggests two successful bouts of breeding. The first bout began with a small group that was followed by a larger Addition.

ISSUE #3: Remove reference to REPEAT BOUT in the final text, replace with MULTIPLE somehow (could just be "second" and not reference the Multiple, since that word is in the first sentence of the stock paragraph.

ISSUE #4: "Breeding Type" in Col BV is "Async" but above mentions "Repeat" aka Multiple.
column80: The recorder didn't pick up the colony very well and all vocalizations are quite faint. FS is never heard, but there is almost continuous chorus, and I can hear the young. I am betting that the young hatch multiple days before I pick them up on the recording. Analysis of the Fledgling Calls suggests there were two successful pulses, with the first pulse starting with a small group and then a larger sub-colony addition. This lead to a Fledling call from 5/1-5/6, 5/22-6/5, and 6/21-6/24. I can estimate the breeding stages as Pulse #1: There was a pulse that started incubating ~4/6, hatched ~4/16, and confirmed to have fledged on 5/1 - and these fledglings hung around for about until 5/6, so hung out for a total of 6 days. Since the recorder was placed on 4/14 I am unable to document the onset of incubation. Hatchlings are too far away to hear until they get a few days old. First nestlings are heard on  There was a sub-colony addition to this first pulse, with this addition starting incubation ~4/28, hatching ~5/8, and was confirmed to have fledged on 5/22 and these fledglings hung around until 6/5, or 15 days. When marking MC - looked for SOLID bands just above and below 2kHz, because of the distance of the chorusing at times, it looks underwhelming compared to other recordings which have Male Song at a closer distance, but they were not a SOLID band. Pulse #2: Once this first pulse was completed, a Replacement Pulse was initiated and incubation began ~5/27, hatching ~6/7, and this pulse fledged on 6/21 and stuck around until 6/24 for a total of 4 days, when the majority of the fledgling calls cease. There is a long tail of occasional fledgling calls that extends through 7/27. I do not know if these are stragglers finishing up a really late breeding attempt, or if these are just fledglings that are re-visiting the area occasionally. Mini Manual was completed.

column78: There were a few birds that started Settlement before the placement of the ARU. There was rain on 6 May at around 1600hr. After this, the ARU did not work on 7 May and 8 May, and only static was recorded. Beginning on around noon on 9 May the recordings begin working again. Presumably the problem was the microphone becomeing wet somehow. The number of Female Chatter detections compared to the number of Nestling Begging Call detections suggests that the Nesting attempted largely failed. There is a three day stretch of 90+ degree weather from 19 May to 21 May that could explain this Partial Abandonment, though the rain on 6 May might also have contributed.
column80: Recordings were faint, but usable. First round of birds started inc on 5/7, then second addition came in on 5/10. First birds would have hatched at ~5/18 (works), then second addition would have hatched ~5/23. 2nd round was much larger, their fledge date would have been ~6/3 (works). So there is one messy pulse of breeding that had an addition after first set started incubating. This results in nestlings being heard only a few days after the last Male Chorus.The FC was never impressive, but there was a large drop in vocalizations on 6/4, so this was picked as the FD.

column78: Because Pattern Matching didn't work well, a mini-manual analysis was performed, and when I was still unsatisfied with the results, I reviewed three recordings from every day. The vocalizations I do detect indicate that the nests are located just outside of audio reach for the ARU. I was able to locate a single Female Whine on 2-June, but it is faint. I believe that the two bouts of Fledgling Begging Calls I am detecting are from birds that are forming creches which are occasionally moving closer to the ARU. I detected the first creche starting 17-Jun. Jason reports that there was a colony of ~100 birds at this location and has an account of food carrying on 29-May, which is consistent with Dispersal of around 17-Jun. The second creche I detected starting 27-July. Timing of this is consistent with a Multiple breeding bout.
column80: There were a few recordings with Male Song, and then at the end of the season a fledgling calls can be heard. Because Pattern Matching did'nt work well a mini-manual analysis was performed, and it also failed to detect Female Chatter and nestling calls. Jason reports that there was a colony of ~100 birds at this location and has an account of food carrying on 5/29. I suspect that for some reason the recorder did not pick up the colony very well, and it only registered the louder vocalizations of the Male Song and Fledgling calls, much like Baja this year. I also suspect that the lack of Male Chorus is just due to the small number of birds. Unfortunately, the lack of robust vocalizations make it so I can't tell much from this site. Based on Fledgling call alone a super tentative guess would be Fledging day of 6/17, whch would put hatch day at ~6/3, and incubation start at ~5/23. But this doesn't agree with ebird reports or field visits. Though it is just a few days off. If Food carries on 3/29 (in-person) was the date of hatching, and if on the longer end for fledgling (14days) then date of fledging would be 6/12. Also, with feeding of Fladglings still seen on Aug, this could have been a continuous nesting site. If this was a continuous nesting site, with the small number of birds I would have had an even lower number of vcalizations to pick up, and this might be beyond the reach of my analysis detection abilities. Also of note, this site was much later than the McCain Wetlands and timing suggests that this could be the same birds as at McCain Wetlands but their second bout of breeding.

column78: A small colony established in April but abandoned just after the first hatchlings were heard. Hatchling Begging Calls were only heard for four days, after which the only Tricolored Blackbird vocoalizations noted were a handful of Male Song. Potential reasons for abandonment are unknown.
column79: A small Tricolored Blackbird colony established at this marsh, nested in emergent vegetation including bulrush or tule and cattails, but the attempt was ultimately abandoned. Early in the deployment, Male Chorus activity indicated that males were present and displaying, but the number of singing males decreased over time. The colony progressed into Brooding, as reflected by the onset of that stage during the recording period, yet Fledgling Begging Calls never developed. All Tricolored Blackbird vocal activity ceased abruptly around the time Brooding would be expected to continue, and only a few birds remained thereafter. These patterns indicate that the nesting attempt advanced into early chick-rearing but was abandoned before fledglings were produced. The cause of abandonment is unknown.
column80: Small colony established but then abandoned. Initially there were more males in MC and then it dwindled to fewer birds.
column84: The Los Vaqueros Reservoir colony is located in a 200 sq m patch of Himalayan Blackberry that is just uphill from a 900 sq m small pond. The blackberry patch is fenced. Surrounding this area is open grassland with grazing cattle.

column78: This was a small Asynchronous colony. There are some really young Hatchling Begging Calls heard starting on 14-May that imply that there might be a Repeating bout of breeding, though there is a scattering of Hatchling Begging Calls just prior to this, consistent with an Asynchrounous colony. Female Chatter never took a break and the started up again, again consistent with an Asynchronous breeding colony, rather than a Repeating. The bulk of the breeding was finished by the end of the month and the fledglings Dispersed. It is unknown if the handful of late hatchings survived to fledging as the ARU was pulled after the bulk of the colony Dispersed.
column80: This was a small asynchronous colony. There are some really young nestlngs heard starting on 14-May that imply that there might be a Replacement bout of breeding, though there are no Female Chatter associated with it. Since I hear some Female Chatter all the way through 4-May I suspect that I am just hearing the "dribbles" from the late nesters. Female Chatter never took a break and the started up again, so in this way it acts more like a Continuously breeding colony, rather than a Replacement. And Female Chatter was a continuous decline from onset of Brooding through 4-May. If the hatchlings I hear on 14-May are from the females that are chattering on 2-May it would make them only a couple of days old. The bulk of the breeding was finished by the end of the month and the fledglings dispersed. It is unknown if the handful of late hatchings survived to fledging.

column78: While the bulk of the breeding was simple and synchronous, there is a long tail with a few straggling vocalizations that suggest that there may have been a handful of either Asynchronous breeding or a Multiple bout of breeding. For example there is a single Female Chatter on 29-Jun as well a Fledgling Begging Call is 7-Jul. I have assigned a Simple breeding pattern as this describes the vast majority of birds.
column79: The breeding attempt was predominantly synchronous, producing a clear sequence of Nestling and Fledgling Begging Calls. A small number of late detections, including isolated Female Chatter and a single late-season Fledgling Begging Call, suggest the presence of a few asynchronous or late-start nests. However, these represented only a minor portion of colony activity, and the overall pattern aligns with a Simple colony structure. Fledgling Begging Calls were abundant and confirm successful reproduction.

column78: A large Tricolored Blackbird colony, estimated at roughly 2,000 birds, established at this reservoir site in Himalayan Blackberry and exhibited a Complex breeding structure showing both Asynchronous and Multiple colony types. The first attempt was Asynchronous: Male Chorus continued through Incubation, Female Chatter overlapped with the period when fledglings were present, and Fledgling Begging Calls showed a prolonged tail, indicating that different portions of the colony were at different breeding stages at the same time. After fledglings from this first attempt dispersed, a second, Asynchronous nesting attempt occurred. Asynchronous was assigned due to the continuation of Female Chatter after Hatchling Begging Calls were heard. Based on the density of vocalizations, the second attempt was much smaller than the first. Both attempts produced fledglings, and the overall outcome for the site was Successful.

column80: This was a highly asynchronous colony. Based on what I hear I believe this was one with a continual expansion/egg laying in each pulse rather than a sub-colony addition. The asynchrony made it challenging to determine MC for pulse 2 asn well as HD for pulse 2. For MC2 I looked for signs of MS at just above Khz 2, and have put a p2c tag at where this band is for many of the recordings. For HD2 I relyed on PMJs to locate recordings with signals of very young nestlings. I then focused on these dates and zoomed in so 8-0 Ktz and about 4 sec were showing on the sonogram. I then looked visually for the signature of very young nestings. It was too hard to try and use my ears to decide if it was a very young nestling or a late nesting from pulse 1.

These are heard throughout the recordings and vocalizations on the last day are of an older youngster, and it is >14 days from hatch date of p2, so while this was extremelt minor, it was also successful.

column78: This was a small colony and detection of the infrequent vocalizations is spotty. There was hardly any Male Chorus, with a stutter start 7-Apr and 8-Apr that was not followed by Female Chatter. The second bout of Male Chorus (23-Apr) was extremely short and was much lighter than the original bout. Only a handful of Nestling Begging Calls are detected, and there is a period of time with no Nestling Begging Calls. This is followed by some Fledgling Begging Calls that are timed such that these are likely the Fledglings from this colony. So while the bulk of birds did not Settle, there were a handful that did and successfully fledged young.

column78: Pattern matching detected robust vocalizations throughout the breeding cycle. A brief period of strong Fledgling Begging Calls in mid-July was attributed to fledglings from the adjacent colony at T27.2. Later, a lighter pulse of Fledgling Begging Calls corresponded to the colony at this location. The timing of both pulses indicates that adults from T27.2 initiated a subsequent nesting attempt at T27.1, and this later attempt successfully fledged young.
column80: It appears that a few fledglings from T27.1 are heard here in T27.1 just after they fledged, confusing analysis. These older birds are not the end of an earlier pulse in T27.1 because there is no evidence of Female Chatter, YNC, or MNC at all in the recordings evn though the recorder was placed with sufficient time to capture these vocalizations if they had been there. Therefore, I am only documenting a single pulse at this location, though because the ON from the other location are around, I need to document this as p2 to tease the two sets of nestlings apart. Additionally, there may be straggler p1 nestlings in the recordings as well, as they don't quite sound like fledglings to me in all of the recordings where I hear ONC when I "shouldn't". Interestingly, I believe that the birds from T27.2 have shifted their second attempt to T27.1 rather than do a replacement pulse in T27.2 and reusing previous nesting areas, thus the marking as p2 would be appropriate. The number of breeding birds is tiny in this pulse. By the end there are just a few straggling nestlings that can be heard to the end of the recordings. I did manage to document at least one fledgling on 7/27/2023 making the Fledgling calls, and I marked these as Simple Call 2 Present. Many of these calls are starting to take on the Flight-call "yip" sound, but their sonograms are much fuzzier and haven't quite developed the crisp sonogram that the adults have. For making summary excel this "second" pulse has been placed in the "first pulse" slot.
column84: Both T27.1 and T27.2 were converted from fallow rice to wetland in 2013 and managed as seasonal wetland until 2014.  In 2015 were put into a long-term permanent/semi-permanent rotation as part of a Giant Garter Snake program, and in 2016 the first Tricolored Blackbird colony was recorded, and has occurred in one of the two ponds each year since.  Pond management includes winter overwater prescribed fire, sheep grazing (they will be detected on the audio recording), and mowing/disking.  Additional details are available upon request.

column78: This ARU did not pick up the colony well, and the vocalizations are quite weak. The first Hatchling Begging Calls are detected on 19-May, however, due to the faint vocalizations, it is likely that the eggs hatched several days prior to this date, and that the first Hatchling Begging Calls were not picked up by the ARU. There is evidence of a Repeating bout of breeding, though there are very few vocalizations detected, and if there was Repeating breeding it appears to have been extremely small. The ARU was collected before any young from this second, extremely small bout would have fledged, and the outcome is unknown.
column80: This ARU did not pick up the colony well, and the vocalizations are quite weak. This could be due to either distance to the colony or possibly the unit being placed in the dry-box upside down. I have manually assessed recordings for the presence of the youngest Nestlings, and on 19-May I begin to hear faint vocalizations, so this date is listed as the first day Hatchling Begging Calls are heard. Due to the faint vocalizations, it is likely that the eggs hatched several days prior to this date, and that the first Hatchling Begging Calls were not picked up by the ARU. A second bout of breeding was initiated, though there were very few vocalizations detected. Those that are detected indicate that at least a few birds initiated a second bout of breeding. The recorder was pulled just after the first Hatchling Begging Calls were expected. No Hatchling Begging Calls were detected for this second bout of breeding, but given the nature of the poor quality of the recordings, this is not unexpected. Therefore, I have marked the outcome from this bout of breeding as Unknown.

column84: The Denverton Creek colony site is in a cattle ranch field in Solano County, California, (38.241, −121.888) at 9.0 m elevation. The colony nested in 0.36 ha of Himalayan Blackberry in the cattle field and adjacent to Creed Road. Grasslands, grazed by cattle, surround the site. The historical size of the colony is estimated to be 500–2,000 adults. We placed the ARU approximately 125 m from the edge of the colony.

column78: What started out as a strong Male Chorus ended up with very few birds completng the cycle. On 4-June most of the birds have left. This coincides with a bout of temperatures exceeding 90F. (Par Abn 6/5/2023, Three days of heat 90+ 6/3-6/5). It has been noted by Bob that temperatures in this range during incubation and onset of brooding can often lead to abandonment. That said, there is at least one fledgling that survived. Because of the fact that most birds left, there are only a handful of vocalizations detected making the estimate of the timing of the breeding phases only approximate. There is also a few Fledgling Begging Calls prior to the Hatching Begging Calls. This could be a bird from an earlier bout of breeding that is traveling with the adults.

column78:
A colony of roughly 300 birds again established at the site. Male Chorus continued through the onset of Hatchling Begging Calls, and Female Chatter persisted for 13 days afterward. These overlapping breeding-stage vocalizations indicate Asynchronous nesting, with groups progressing through stages on different schedules.

Fledgling Begging Calls increased steadily through mid-May and then showed a sharp decline, marking the dispersal of creches. In-person visits conducted by volunteers aligned with the timing inferred acoustically; fledglings were observed dispersing on the same date as the drop in vocalizations. No disturbances or weather-related acoustic signatures coincided with any stage transitions.

column78: This colony had a Complex form of breeding and exhibited both Addition and Multiple forms. After the first set of birds commenced Brooding, there was an Addition on 4-May. These new arrivals would have occupied new nesting sites, as the first set of individuals were still Brooding. There was a third bout of Male Chorus that occurs approximately at the time the first Fledgling Begging Calls from the first set of birds are heard, that suggest a Multiple bout of breeding by the very first set of birds. These birds from the Addition also had a Repeating bout of breeding and Hatchling Begging Calls are seen for a fourth time. The Fledgling Begging Calls From the firs three bouts of breeding overlap, and it is not possible to determine their dispersal dates. There is a large drop in Fledgling Begging Calls on 14 June suggesting that some of the fledglings dispersed on that date.The ARU was collected before this last set of birds would have fledged, and if they were successful is unknown.
column80: This colony had a Complex form of breeding and exhibited both Sub-colony Addition and Replacement forms. After the first bout of breeding commenced Brooding, there was a Sub-colony Addition on 4-May. These new arrivals would have occupied new nesting sites, as the original individuals that formed the colony were still brooding, and thus nests were occupied. In addition, there was a third bout of Male Chorus that occurs approximately at the time the first Fledgling Begging Calls are heard, that suggest that this is a Replacement bout of breeding where the nesting sites previously occupied are reused for another bout of breeding. This Replacement bout is much smaller than the original bout of breeding, and there are only a handful of Female Chatter in June, and only a few Hatchling Begging Calls in June as well. This second weak bout might have also shown a replacement for the sub-colony addition, though it was hard to document, as it was obscured by the vocalizations from the overlapping, and much larger bout of breeding from the first bout, but the presence of Fledgling Begging Calls into mid-June imply that this Replacement bout of at the orignal nesting sites, was also successful. Additionally, there is evidence that there was a Replacement bout of breeding at the Sub-colony Addition sites in that there are hatchlings heard on June 13, which is 28 days after the hatchlings from the first subcolony addition are heard. NOTE - SHOULD ADD THE BLACK ARROWS FOR EACH OF THE HATCHLING BOUTS ONTO THE CHART.

column84: Both T27.1 and T27.2 were converted from fallow rice to wetland in 2013 and managed as seasonal wetland until 2014.  In 2015 were put into a long-term permanent/semi-permanent rotation as part of a Giant Garter Snake program, and in 2016 the first Tricolored Blackbird colony was recorded, and has occurred in one of the two ponds each year since.  Pond management includes winter overwater prescribed fire, sheep grazing (they will be detected on the audio recording), and mowing/disking.  Additional details are available upon request.
column86: Jennifer Isola, Michael Derrico, Mike Carpenter

column78:
Early-season activity is high, with strong Male Chorus throughout March and April. Activity drops abruptly on 25 April. In late April, only a few Female Chatter were detected, indicating that although Male Chorus was strong, just a handful of females were recruited to nest. A site visit on 29 April confirmed this weak recruitment: only ~50 birds remained from the original ~500, and only a few females were carrying food. Sparse Fledgling Begging Calls in late May–mid June indicate that a small number of nests succeeded. There is no date of Dispersal for this bout of breeding. This is because the Fledgling Begging Calls from this bout continue through the onset of the next bout of Fledgling Begging Calls.

A second attempt initiated later in the season and proceeded normally. It was Successful. The marked increase in Fledgling Begging Calls on 21 June most likely represents the fledging date for the Retry attempt. 

During this period, two sources of disturbance were documented:
• Feral pigs entered the nesting substrate, with eleven recordings of feral pig vocalizations between 24 March and 1 April and their presence was noted on 1 Apr during a site visit.
• Coyotes were present and may have used pig-created access paths; five recordings with coyote vocalizations were detected between 29 March and 7 May and site visits noted their presence near the colony from 29 Apr to 24 Jun.

Although these disturbances could have contributed to the colony's Partial Abandonment of its first breeding attempt, strong Male Chorus continued throughout the period when feral pigs were active, suggesting that feral pigs alone were not the primary driver of abandonment, and coyotes were present throughout the second successful breeding attempt.
column79:
Early-season activity is high, with strong Male Chorus throughout March and April. Activity drops abruptly on 25 April. A weak bout of Female Chatter in late April indicates that although most birds abandoned, a small number of females remained and nested. A site visit on 29 April confirmed Partial Abandonment: only ~50 birds remained from the original ~500, and only a few females were carrying food. Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls were not detected for this first attempt, but sparse Fledgling Begging Calls in late May–mid June indicate that a small number of nests succeeded, but the overall pattern is consistent with Partial Abandonment.

A second Retry attempt initiated later in the season and proceeded normally. It was successful. The marked increase in Fledgling Begging Calls on 21 June most likely represents the fledging date for the Retry attempt. 

During this period, two sources of disturbance were documented:
• Feral pigs entered the nesting substrate, with eleven recordings of feral pig vocalizations between 24 March and 1 April and their presence was noted on 1 Apr during a site visit.
• Coyotes were present and may have used pig-created access paths; five recordings with coyote vocalizations were detected between 29 March and 7 May and site visits noted their presence near the colony from 29 Apr to 24 Jun.

Although these disturbances could have contributed to the colony's Partial Abandonment of its first breeding attempt, strong Male Chorus continued throughout the period when feral pigs were active, suggesting that feral pigs alone were not the primary driver of abandonment, and coyotes were present throughout the second successful breeding attempt.
