column78: This colony gets a slow start and then continuously ramps up its breeding effort. There was an first bout of breeding that was either too small or too distant from the recorder to pick up many Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations. This first bout did successfully produce fledglings, and several recordings have Fledgling Begging Calls present on 5/19. I did not locate any recordings prior to this with Hatchling of Nestling Begging Calls. At about a month from the onset of this first weak bout there is a replacement bout that had Continuous breeding that began in the middle of May and it continues into July. This is the bout that I have been able to assign dates as there were plentiful vocalizations.

This was the second reorder placed at the same location as Main Pond 2. For some reason this recorder stopped recording much earlier than the other recorder. Analysis of these recordings gave the same results as for the analysis of the Main Pond 1 ARU.

The colony again followed an Asynchronous structure. Male Chorus continued for several days after the first Hatchling Begging Calls were detected, and Female Chatter was present well into the Brooding period. Only 27 Female Chatter detections were validated throughout the season, substantially fewer than expected, likely because continuous Male Chorus and strong Nestling Begging Calls masked these quieter vocalizations.

Despite reduced detectability of Female Chatter, the sequence of stage-specific vocalizations was intact, and Fledgling Begging Calls were detected throughout June, confirming successful fledging. As in previous years, no disturbances or abrupt environmental events were detected in the audio record.

column78: Male Chorus and Female Chatter indicated early nesting activity, followed by two distinct rounds of Begging Calls. Timing and density patterns show sequential nesting bouts, each producing fledglings. A small number of Nestling and Fledgling Begging Call detections in July suggest the possibility of a limited third bout; however, these detections are also consistent with a few late or Asynchronous nests associated with the predominantly Synchronous second attempt. The colony is therefore classified as Multiple.
column84: in marsh at northwest corner of lake

column78: A strong pattern of early-season vocalizations was followed by a sudden decline beginning on 13 June. Nestling Begging Calls persisted long enough to indicate that a portion of the brood successfully fledged, but Fledgling Begging Calls were not detected. The abrupt reduction in colony activity shortly after the onset of Brooding, coinciding with a heat event, is consistent with Partial Abandonment.
column80: Need to check manually if there are any fledgling calls. The colony was extremely small, and only occassional vocalizations are heard. Nestling calls are heard for more than 14 days. I believe I have noted that when colonies are very very small the nestlings are not as loud when the reach fledlging age, and I get none to very short interval of Fledgling calls.
column84: Both T27.1 and T27.2 were converted from fallow rice to wetland in 2013 and managed as seasonal wetland until 2014.  In 2015 were put into a long-term permanent/semi-permanent rotation as part of a Giant Garter Snake program, and in 2016 the first Tricolored Blackbird colony was recorded, and has occurred in one of the two ponds each year since.  Pond management includes winter overwater prescribed fire, sheep grazing (they will be detected on the audio recording), and mowing/disking.  Additional details are available upon request.

column78: A brief rise in Male Song and Male Chorus suggested that birds investigated the site, but Female Chatter and Begging Calls were absent, and no colony ever established. This coincided with the timing of Partial Abandonment at site T27.1 and these birds may have been ones relocating after the Partical Abandonment.
column80: I think all I am hearing is the distant colony that is better heard from the other reorder.

column78: Three ARUs documented a broad colony, and the East recorder captured the primary nesting activity. One strong synchronous nesting pulse dominated the acoustic record. A faint tail of Begging Calls suggested a small number of asynchronous nests, consistent with Female Chatter persisting several days beyond the onset of early Begging Calls.

column88: Email from Ben on 2/8/2025: "I attached a photo of the "Dollar Marsh" area where Tricolored Blackbird nested in 2024. This area remains the largest stronghold of cattails along the PVP portion of Panoche Creek. When I deployed the AMs, Tricolored Blackbird were well distributed among the cattails throughout this entire area. As nesting began in earnest, it appeared most of the birds(1000-1500) were concentrated in the area directly surrounding AM#42-EAST. There was another group(several hundred) across the marsh adjacent to AM#06-SOUTH. The Tricolored Blackbird using the patchy cattails south of AM#26WEST did not stick around as I thought they might, and I have little hope they were able to successfully nest in that area."

column78: Dave only had permission to leave the recorder in place for a few days. Based on the presence of fledgling calls, and his in-person report of seeing fledglings out of the nest, this colony was successful, though the timing of the phenological stages cannot be determined.

Recorder was placed while birds were present, and Bob noted that he saw about 2,000 birds and some females carrying nesting material. The recorder appears to be distant to the colony and vocalizations are faint. Male Chrous was not detected until four days after the placement of the recorder. Only three recordings of Female Chatter were detected. After 4/26 only a handful of recordings contained Tricolored Blackbird vocalizations. I have marked this as no colony formation because I did not detect any significant Female Chatter after the Male Chorus ceased.

There was a large, 30,000 birds that settled and began nesting. There were two ARUs deployed, one here at "Little Ramona" and the other at "Bridge Street Pond". Both locations Abandoned on the same date. Also at both locations helicopters are heard. I believe Rose said helicopters used the ponds for water, and suspects this caused the birds to abandon.
